{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3d0ceca2-b15a-4354-879a-0a463300e030","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request** — each request gets its own scope. In MAUI, there are **no HTTP requests**, so the default scope is the **application lifetime**. This means `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton` — your DbContext is reused everywhere, causing stale/persisted data.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — gives a new instance each time it's injected.\n\n2. **Use a DbContext factory** (preferred):\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>(options =>\n       options.UseSqlite(\"...\"));\n   ```\n   Then inject `IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>` and create short-lived contexts:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\nThe factory approach gives you explicit control over context lifetime, which is the recommended pattern for non-HTTP apps like MAUI, WPF, and Blazor desktop.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"24d7c1c0-8ffb-45c0-b09b-e495073bc256","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping — specifically why `AddScoped` behaves differently in MAUI than in ASP.NET Core.\n\nThis is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, a \"scope\" is created per HTTP request, so `AddScoped` gives you a new instance per request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request scope — the app has a single scope that lives for the entire application lifetime. So `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton` in MAUI, meaning your DbContext is reused across all page navigations.\n\n\nI should explain this clearly with a practical example to help them understand the implications.","outputTokens":444},"id":"4cf869d9-18d6-453b-894a-d755329f5617","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:43:05.878Z","parentId":"496bc7da-c030-4ff1-8e00-c40aac94a6f6"}
